SonarQube → Is your code well-written? 
OWASP(Open Worldwide Application Security Project) → What are the common security risks? 
Trivy → Is your app/image actually vulnerable right now?


owasp scans security vulnerabilities in web applications,files and images, while trivy scans for vulnerabilities 
in container images and filesystems. SonarQube is a code quality and security analysis tool that can be used to 
identify bugs, code smells, and security vulnerabilities in your codebase.

reports are saved inside the containers.

# to create trivy container the docker compose file is:
trivy:
    image: aquasec/trivy:latest
    container_name: trivy
    volumes:
      - /var/run/docker.sock:/var/run/docker.sock
    entrypoint: ["sleep", "infinity"]

app:
    image: nginx:latest
    container_name: nginx-app
    ports:
      - "8080:80"

# now run the compose file
docker compose up -d
# now exec into trivy container
docker compose exec -it trivy sh
# now scan the nginx-app container for vulnerabilities
trivy image nginx:latest
# to scan a specific image
trivy image <image_name>:<tag>
# to scan a filesystem
trivy fs /path/to/directory
# to generate report in json format
trivy image -f json -o report.json nginx:latest
# to generate report in html format
trivy image -f template -o report.html --template "@contrib/html.tpl" nginx:latest

# to run trivy without enter docker container
docker exec -it trivy trivy image nginx:latest

# to scan only high and critical vulnerabilities
docker exec -it trivy trivy image \
  --severity HIGH,CRITICAL \
  nginx:latest

# generate report in json
docker exec trivy trivy image \
  -f json \
  -o /tmp/nginx-trivy.json \
  nginx:latest
# copy it out
docker cp trivy:/tmp/nginx-trivy.json .

=======================set up owasp zap proxy with docker compose=========================
OWASP is a non-profit organization that defines application security risks, 
standards, and best practices. It does not scan applications itself but provides
frameworks like the OWASP Top 10 and tools such as ZAP that help teams identify and mitigate security vulnerabilities.

# craete docker compose file with the following content
zap:
    image: zaproxy/zap-stable
    container_name: zap
    ports:
      - "8090:8080"
    volumes:
      - ./data/zap-reports:/zap/wrk
    command: ["sleep", "9999999"]

# now run the compose file
docker compose up -d
# now access owasp zap proxy at http://localhost:8090

# now to scan a target website using owasp zap proxy
# exec into zap container
docker compose exec -it zap sh
# now run the following command to scan the target website
zap-cli quick-scan --self-contained --start-options '-config api.disablekey=true' http
://example.com

docker exec -it zap zap-baseline.py -t http://nginx-app:80 -r report.html
# to generate report in html format
zap-cli report -o /zap/wrk/owasp-zap-report.html -f html
# to generate report in xml format
zap-cli report -o /zap/wrk/owasp-zap-report.xml -f xml
# copy the report to host machine
docker cp zap:/zap/wrk/owasp-zap-report.html .
# open the report in browser
xdg-open owasp-zap-report.html

# to scan a service running 
docker compose exec zap zap-baseline.py -t http://app:80 -r zap-report.html

=======================set up sonarqube with docker compose=========================
# create a docker compose file with the following content
sonarqube:
    image: sonarqube:lts
    container_name: sonarqube
    ports:
      - "9000:9000"
    environment:
      SONAR_JDBC_USERNAME: sonar
      SONAR_JDBC_PASSWORD: sonar
      SONAR_SEARCH_JAVAOPTS: "-Xms512m -Xmx512m"
      SONAR_WEB_JAVAOPTS: "-Xms512m -Xmx512m"
    
    volumes:
      - ./sonarqube/data:/opt/sonarqube/data
      - ./sonarqube/logs:/opt/sonarqube/logs
      - ./sonarqube/extensions:/opt/sonarqube/extensions


mkdir -p ./sonarqube/{data,logs,extensions}
sudo chown -R 1000:1000 ./sonarqube
chmod -R 755 ./sonarqube


# now run the compose file
docker compose up -d
# now access sonarqube at http://localhost:9000
